args: The punishment for the sin of survival is\nruination. The hammer of annihilation\nshall fall on those who slew their king.
Now let the world become abyss.
Hearken to me, my king! Bear witness to\nthe dissolution of a world bereft of you!
This mana fount is ruined, too.\nI sense no power in it whatsoever.
This is the third mana fount that we've\nfound destroyed here in Alberia.\nWho is doing this, and why?
The world would be unmade without mana;\nI can think of no explanation but that they\nseek to throw the world into disarray.
We'll be in dire straits if this keeps up.\nI'm going to take a look over there, Cleo.\nYou mind checking out this area?
One could not make a mana fount wither\nwithout a considerable degree of power.\nA fiend, perhaps? A magical weapon?
It has been some time, Cleo,\nyet your visage is unchanged.
And I you, for you are she who abandoned\nher king to live on in a world bereft of him!
Come, Cleo. Come and accept your\npunishment for remaining in this world.
Ah, so this one is the new sacrifice for\npeace—it is a role well-suited for a puppet\nornamented in lies.

But you will not get to fulfill even that
role. Once I sever the mana from this
land, there will be nothing left for you to
stake your life for.
Then YOU are the one who has been\ndestroying the mana founts, Tartarus!
Do you know this person, Cleo?
One might have called us allies, once.
He is one of the dragons who fought\nalongside King Alberius in the Second\nWar of Binding three centuries ago...
So you swore a pact with Alberius?\nIn that case, why are you going around\ndestroying the mana founts?!
Is it not apparent? I seek the ruination\nof the Kingdom of Alberia.
But why would a loyal servant of Alberius\ndestroy the kingdom he so loved?
The kingdom he ＂loved＂?\n...Don't make me laugh.
My reason for destruction is revenge.\nNothing more or less.
The kingdom is guilty of his murder, and I\nshall never be able to quell his regrets\nif I do not see it razed to ash and bone.
Murder? What are you talking about?!\nThe king gave his all and last for Alberia!
Which is why I name it murderer.
This kingdom chose the path of sacrifice.\nOne life for the world, and for all who live\nwith it—human, dragon, and other.
They killed the king. YOU killed the king.\nWith my own eyes, I watched it happen.

I watched as the king suffered the
excruciating pain that is the price of the
Blood Casket—the ritual for sealing away
the Other—giving of his life for others.
I never heard a word of any of this\nfrom His Majesty...
He did not wish for his people to harbor\nunease in regards to his duty, as it called\nfor him to surrender his own life.
That cannot be! It was not duty alone\nwhich drove him to fight!
He was a kind man! He fought for his\nideals of justice, to protect his people!
Justice? JUSTICE? Aaaah ha ha ha!
Do you know what I have hated most\nthese past three hundred years, Cleo?\nThe exact ＂justice＂ of which you speak.
He was worshipped as a hero—and thus\nforced to push the boulder of justice up\na mountain of war and battle!

All voices cried out to name him hero,
and so he fashioned himself into the
fulcrum upon which the world turned
toward peace.
Y-yes, it's true that we all counted on\nKing Alberius a great deal—perhaps\neven too much—but we never... I mean...
Thus is justice a breeding ground for\ndiseased philosophies that drive one to\ncast aside their life for the sake of others.

The innocence of bystanders takes all from
those who offer themselves up entire—
and a world that valorizes such a thing
is a world gone awry.

Thus will I bring unto that world a total
annihilation—of humans, dragons, and the
very land itself! I will ruin the rotted world
that so values this ＂justice＂!
Day after day, you trample upon the land\nwhere our king passed without a care in\nyour head! Both of you are guilty of this.
If you would revenge yourself upon all in\nthis land, I will protect them to my last.
For to protect the world my king sought\nto save is to protect his very soul itself!

Fool... FOOL! How unbelievable that you
cannot distinguish between that which one
has wished for and that which one was
FORCED to make his wish!

I shall bring down my hammer upon this
world that forces the sacrifice of a king,
and I shall bring down my hammer upon
the peace it so desperately craves!
Indeed, we are the jaws of destruction\nleft unto this world.
O king, I swear to you now that I shall\nsee your soul liberated from this world.\nKing Alberius, be my aegis!
